Why use ExEmPLAR

The purpose of this tool is to act as an interface with knowledge graphs tools in building queries and returning results which can be manipulated, annotated, and exported for further evaluation.

Features in this tool also enable query caching and transfer into the Neo4j Robokop environment.

Exemplar landing page at https://www.exemplar.mml.unc.edu/

How to make a query

Start with writing down a question. Consider how to frame your question into a direction [i.e. chemical leads to effect].

Node name resolver

Identify your start and ending points. ExEmPLAR has built in term checking functions, but your question may benefit from some built in specificity [i.e. heart disease could be narrowed down more specifically to instances encoded as chemically-induced-cardiotoxicity]. Check out your terms using renci name resolver to find the specific ID you need.

Run ExEmPLAR locally

ExEmPLAR can be run locally by first forking the associated GitHub. Integrate it with your local environment using for example GitHub Desktop, and start the “dash_app.py” located within the repo “AOP-COP-Path-Extractor” by running python “wdir\GitHub\AOP-COP-Path-Extractor\dash_app.py”

Use case

Cardio tox and Flame Retardants

To address the question of an example relationship between flame retardants and cardiovascular outcomes, I queried Tetrabromobisphenol A ; 1,2,5,6,9,10-Hexabromocyclododecane ; & Triethyl phosphate towards the cardiovascular toxicity endpoints: MONDO:0005267, UMLS:C0876994, and cardiovascular disorder. As characterized below.

Narrow results

The above results are flooded with disease associations, namely cardiovascular disorder. Let’s narrow them down.

Parse existing query

First filter out first cardiovascular disorder itself and get frequency counts of the remainder. Realize that there are many other disease associations and then limit table to those with seven or fewer characters, reasoning that the gene/protein names would likely be the remainder.

##  [1] ABCB1  AKT1   APLN   APP    ATP2A1 CASP3  CAT    Edema  IFNG   IL1B  
## [11] IL6    MAPK1  MAPK3  MMP9   NFE2L2 PPARG  PTGS2  TNF    TTR   
## 19 Levels: ABCB1 AKT1 APLN APP ATP2A1 CASP3 CAT Edema IFNG IL1B IL6 ... TTR

Above amounts to a list of implicated genes. Adjusting the initial query by requiring an intermediary node to result in terms of gene or gene product supplies the relevant information without overloading on associations.

New query - gene hop 1

Below is a query with two paths of two hops each. In the first query gene or gene product is required in the first hop, whereas the second query has the second hop requiring gene or gene product.

df <- as_tibble(read_csv(paste0(wdir,"20230126_mml_exemplar_use_ex_q2.csv")))

PCA

PCA is computed if unlabeled on the degree weighted path counts of start node entries.
Therefore, this feature is best used to visualize many start node entries rather than the few presented here.

pca on flame retardant
